[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.1 Isolation can be due to 
[normal]geography, mobility, lack of awareness, cultural barriers
[normal] changed personal circumstances, such as the loss of a partner who drove,
[normal] or financial concerns. Community engagement through parish transport representatives and transport forums seeks to overcome a
[normal]wareness and cultural barriers whilst information provision at bus stops and stations, through electronic media and 
[normal]via 
[normal]printed material seeks to ensure that services are well promoted.
[normal]3.2 Hampshire County Council has been successful in achieving the re-o
[normal]pening of Chandler’s Ford railway station, and as a statutory consultee maintaining and improving services here and 
[normal]at 
[normal]other, often
[normal] rural
[normal],
[normal] stations. The County Council actively supports two local Community Rail Partnerships which help develop the Chandler’
[normal]s Ford line and remove
[normal]d
[normal] the closure risk of the Lymington branch.
[normal] Community involvement is 
[normal]central
[normal] to success.
[normal]3.3 
[normal]Bus users are widely represented among older and disadvantaged groups and the County Council has been successful in projects such as the A3 
[normal]Star corridor and the Eclipse Bus Rapid Transit project between Fareham and Gosport
[normal]. These have helped
[normal] boost bus use to a twenty year high across Hampshire as well as promoting economic activity in deprived areas.
[normal] 
[normal]http://www3.hants.gov.uk/tfsh/eclipse.htm
[normal]3.4 Conventional buses are mass transit and work best on highly populated corridors. A simpler strategic network of frequent services supported by demand responsive or community transport services s
[normal]eems the most sustainable. This enables investment in modern easy access vehicles and allows rising fuel and wage costs to be recovered from passenger fares.
[normal]3.5 Hampshire introduced the pioneering Cango flexible bus model in 2001. This combines fixed poin
[normal]t, turn up and go travel, with bookable flexible routeing to provide a scheduled public bus which can meet the travel needs of dispersed communities.
[normal]4.1 Hampshire has an active and well-developed community transport sector.  It follows a tool-box approach rather than a single solution and the County Council 
[normal]underpins a partnership with third
[normal] sector
[normal] organisatio
[normal]ns
[normal], volunteers and district and parish councils. The County Council contributes
[normal] significant
[normal] funding, 
[normal]offer
[normal]s start-up advice
[normal] and grants
[normal], supports volunteer recruitment and provides a range of best 
[normal]practice sh
[normal]aring sessions, road shows, nationally recognised 
[normal]training programmes
[normal] such as MiDAS
[normal] and professional support and advice
[normal]. 
[normal]4.2 
[normal]This 
[normal]strength of the community transport sector in Hampshire 
[normal]is in part due to the partnership approach which the authority has de
[normal]veloped since the early 1980s. The sector is diverse with a wide range of organisations providing transport in the county, this includes: 
