[normal]4.3 
[normal]Community transport 
[normal]is not a low-cost or no-cost option.
[normal] Community-led organisations 
[normal]depend on loca
[normal]l willingness and the availability of volunteers. This can make equality of provision 
[normal]between 
[normal]areas difficult to achieve. Many individuals and organisations value their independence. The County Council has found that the toolbox approach, with a range of s
[normal]olutions, training and support and 
[normal]the 
[normal]use of commercial services such as Taxishares
[normal],
[normal] where appropriate
[normal],
[normal] can prove effective at meeting travel needs.
[normal]5.1 
[normal]Opportunities to extend rail provision are limited and a c
[normal]onventional bus
[normal] service
[normal] is only cost-effective where passenger numbers warrant it. Those living close to urban bus networks in Hampshire are enjoying some of the best frequencies and 
[normal]most 
[normal]modern vehicles that have ever been provided
[normal], helped by County Council investment in Qualit
[normal]y Bus Partnerships
[normal]. 
[normal]Those who
[normal] live in a rural area
[normal] on a busy inter-urban 
[normal]bus route
[normal] 
[normal]often have
[normal] services 
[normal]that 
[normal]are 
[normal]as good as those of
[normal] fifty years ago, apart from evenings and Sundays where higher
[normal] car ownership has taken custom.  I
[normal]n other areas new solutions 
[normal]are needed.
[normal]5.2 Hampshire has shown that Cango and community bus services can provide scheduled services in a different way. 
[normal]In addition
[normal], Hampshire has developed Taxi-shares to offer a timetabled service at local bus fares. They do require users to pre-boo
[normal]k but this means that the service only runs when required 
[normal]so 
[normal]that costs 
[normal]are
[normal] contained and a service 
[normal]retained
[normal] whe
[normal]re
[normal] a conventional bus would be unaffordable.
[normal] 
[normal]http://www3.hants.gov.uk/passengertransport/communitytransport/taxishares.htm
[normal]6.1 In Hampshire, over 70% of bus services are provided commercially, that is funded by passenger fares
[normal]. The County Council supports these services through Quality bus Partnerships, Better Bus Area and Local Sustainable Transport Fund projects, bus stop and bus station infrastructure investment and information provision. 
[normal]6.2 Bus operating costs such as fue
[normal]l and wages have been rising faster than general inflation meaning that services can become uneconomic and any replacement might look for subsidy funding from the local authority. Bus operators claim that concessionary fares reimbursement
[normal] does not meet los
[normal]t fares income, whilst BSOG has been reduced.
[normal] Both have a poten
[normal]tial to increase pressure on a finite
[normal] bus subsidy budget.
[normal]6.3 Concessionary fares reimbursement has placed a burden on Travel Concession Authorities, which are often Local Transport Authorities
[normal],
[normal] a
[normal]s central g
[normal]overnment funding is based on a formula according to population whilst cost are incurred according to use resulting in a funding shortfall.
[normal] The eligible passholder population is projected to rise and central government funding to fall.
[normal]6.4 Av
[normal]ailability of free concessionary travel means that chargeable services such as Dial-a-Ride are expected to accept passes or offer a discount – in Hampshire, the County Council subsidises half fare travel on Dial-a-Ride for concessionary pass holders. Simil
[normal]arly, residents sometimes press for a bus service to be provided so that they can use their free passes even though there is a rail alternative offering reasonable, but not free, fares. 
[normal]Both are cost pressures.
[normal]6.5 As facilities such as health, Post Office
[normal]s or banking centralise to save costs, there is an expectation that public transport will be available
[normal]. This can involve
[normal] travel to 
[normal]locat
[normal]ions away from the previous public transport 
[normal]network, longer journeys than are a
[normal]ttractive to bus users or 
[normal]appointment
[normal] ti
[normal]mes that are earlier than the existing timetable can accommodate. All these can be additional costs on a finite bus subsidy budget, and although vital journeys for the users, 
[normal]low and fragmented 
[normal]demand mean
[normal]s
[normal] that continuing subsidy would b
[normal]e required
[normal].
[normal]6.5 Fo
[normal]r community transport, an ageing population points to a continuing demand, but family or work commitments reduce 
[normal]the 
[normal]availa
[normal]bility of volunteers 
[normal]while
[normal] funding 
[normal]pressures on upper-tier and district councils put
[normal] budgets at risk. A variety of approaches as demo
[normal]nstrated by Hampshire is essential
[normal] but costs will remain
[normal].
[normal]6.6 
[normal]Age UK 
[normal]in their 
[normal]report on Later Life in Rural England
[normal] of
[normal] July 2013
[normal] recognise that lower rural population density and greater distances will increase journey cost per person and seek recognition of this through a ‘rural premium’ and ‘rural-proofing to take into account policy impacts. Hampshire County Council seeks to add
[normal]ress this through use of voluntary car schemes and scheduled Taxishare services.
[normal]6.7 The benefits to the individual, to the wider community and the savings on health and social care budgets which come from good personal mobility through effective public an
[normal]d community transport can be difficult to quantify and 
[normal]any financial benefit
[normal]s would appear under a different budget heading to that where the cost falls.
